[[Image:Birthball.jpg|thumb|right|Typical Birthing Ball]] A '''birthing ball''' or '''labor ball''' is a large air–filled rubber ball (a [[gym ball]] about {{convert|70|cm}} in diameter)<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.babycentre.co.uk/a1048463/using-a-birthing-ball | title=Using a birthing ball | publisher=[[BabyCentre]] | date=October 2014 | accessdate=January 17, 2017}}</ref> that a woman can sit on during [[Childbirth|labor]]. A birthing ball allows the woman to rock back and forth seated on a softer surface. A woman on a birthing ball may need a support person to keep her steady. A birthing ball may be especially useful during [[back labor]]. Hospital policies on birthing balls vary, in part because the balls provide a somewhat unsteady seat, some hospitals are concerned about their safety if a woman falls during [[birth]]. It is often used during [[natural childbirth]].
