[[File:SelectionOfProcessedMeats.jpg|thumb|Various types of processed meat for sale at a grocery store]] '''Processed meat''' is considered to be any [[meat]] which has been modified in order either to improve its taste or to extend its [[shelf life]]. Methods of [[meat processing]] include [[Salting (food)|salting]], [[Curing (food preservation)|curing]], [[Fermentation in food processing|fermentation]], and [[Smoking (cooking)|smoking]]. Processed meat is usually composed of [[pork]] or [[beef]], but also [[poultry]], while it can also contain [[offal]] or [[meat by-products]] such as [[blood]]. Processed meat products include [[bacon]], [[ham]], [[sausage]]s, [[salami]], [[corned beef]], [[Jerky|beef jerky]], [[Potted meat|canned meat]] and meat-based sauces. Meat processing includes all the processes that change fresh meat with the exception of simple mechanical processes such as cutting, grinding or mixing.<ref name="Pearson">{{Cite book|title = Processed Meats|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XcPrCAAAQBAJ|publisher = Springer Science & Business Media|date = 2012-12-06|isbn = 9789401096928|first = A. M.|last = Pearson|first2 = F. W.|last2 = Tauber}}Introduction [https://books.google.gr/books?id=XcPrCAAAQBAJ&lpg=PR1&dq=Processed%20meat&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false]</ref>
[[International Agency for Research on Cancer|IARC]] at the [[World Health Organization]] classifies processed meat as a [[List of IARC Group 1 carcinogens|Group 1, carcinogenic to humans]], since it has found sufficient evidence that consumption of processed meat by humans causes [[colorectal cancer]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = You might be surprised by what counts as processed meat|url = http://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-processed-meat-2015-10|website = Business Insider|accessdate = 2015-11-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = What is processed meat? - BBC News|url = https://www.bbc.com/news/health-34620617|website = BBC News|accessdate = 2015-11-19|language = en-GB}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = https://www.iarc.fr/en/media-centre/pr/2015/pdfs/pr240_E.pdf|title = IARC Monographs evaluate consumption of red meat and processed meat|date = 26 October 2015|accessdate = 19 Nov 2015|website = |publisher = [[International Agency for Research on Cancer|IARC]]|last = |first = }}</ref>
A 2016 report by the [[American Institute for Cancer Research]] and the [[World Cancer Research Fund]] found that processed meat consumption increased the risk of [[stomach cancer]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.wcrf.org/sites/default/files/Stomach-Cancer-2016-Report.pdf | title=Diet, nutrition, physical activity and stomach cancer | publisher=[[American Institute for Cancer Research]] and [[World Cancer Research Fund]] | date=21 April 2016 | accessdate=23 April 2016}}</ref> A 2012 paper by Bryan et. al. identified ''[[Helicobacter pylori]]'' as a potential causative agent that warranted further study.<ref>{{cite journal|title=The role of red and processed meat in colorectal cancer development: a perspective|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0309174014000564|accessdate=2016-12-07|doi=10.1016/j.meatsci.2014.02.011|volume=97|pages=583–596|journal=Meat Science}}</ref>
Meat processing began as soon as people realized that cooking and salting prolongs the life of fresh meat. It is not known when this took place, however, the process of salting and [[Drying (food)|sun-drying]] was recorded in Ancient Egypt, while using ice and snow is credited to early Romans, while [[canning]] was developed by [[Nicolas Appert]] who received in 1810 a prize for his invention from the French government.<ref name="Pearson" />
The [[preservative]] [[sodium nitrite]] (E250) (mixed into curing-salt) is well known for its role in inhibiting the growth of [[clostridium botulinum]] bacteria spores in processed and refrigerated meats. A principal concern about sodium nitrite is the formation of carcinogenic [[nitrosamines]] in meats containing sodium nitrite when meat is charred or overcooked. Such carcinogenic nitrosamines can also be formed from the reaction of [[nitrite]] with secondary [[amines]] under acidic conditions (such as occurs in the human stomach) as well as during the curing process used to preserve meats.{{Citation needed|date=October 2016}}
Nitrate and nitrite are consumed from plant foods as well as animal foods, with 80% of a typical person's nitrate consumption coming from vegetables, especially leafy and root vegetables such as spinach and beets.<ref name="Public Health Statement for NITRATE and NITRITE">{{Cite web |url=https://www.atsdr.cdc.gov/phs/phs.asp?id=1448&tid=258 |title=Public Health Statement for NITRATE and NITRITE}}</ref> Some nitrate is converted to nitrite in the human body.<ref name="Public Health Statement for NITRATE and NITRITE"/> [[Nitrite]] is generally recognized as safe by the [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]].
== Further reading == *[http://www.fao.org/docrep/010/ai407e/AI407E02.htm Meat processing technology for small- to medium-scale producers] Gunter Heinz, Peter Hautzinger, Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) Regional Office for Asia and the Pacific (RAP), Bangkok, 2007, {{ISBN|978-974-7946-99-4}} *{{Cite book|title = Processed Meats|url = https://books.google.com/books?id=XcPrCAAAQBAJ|publisher = Springer Science & Business Media|date = 2012-12-06|isbn = 9789401096928|first = A. M.|last = Pearson|first2 = F. W.|last2 = Tauber}}Introduction [https://books.google.gr/books?id=XcPrCAAAQBAJ&lpg=PR1&dq=Processed%20meat&pg=PA1#v=onepage&q&f=false] *[https://www.theguardian.com/news/2018/mar/01/bacon-cancer-processed-meats-nitrates-nitrites-sausages Yes, bacon is really killing us] Bee Wilson, The Guardian, 2018-03-01. ==References== {{reflist}}
