{{Automatic taxobox | image = Tawuia Chuaria Longfengshania.jpg | image_caption = reconstruction as a slime mold-like organism | taxon = Tawuia | authority = }}
'''''Tawuia''''' is a millimetric disc-shaped, most likely multicellular [[macrofossil]] from the [[Neoproterozoic]]. It is considered to be synonymous with '''''Chuaria''''' and '''''Longfengshania''''', which, in turn, are thought to represent different life stages of the same organism.<ref name=trois>{{Citation | author = | first=B. | title = Trois classes de fossiles precambriens pour un meme taxon | language = French | url = http://www.sciencedirect.com/science?_ob=ArticleURL&_udi=B6X1G-4B4XBDC-H&_user=10&_rdoc=1&_fmt=&_orig=search&_sort=d&view=c&_acct=C000050221&_version=1&_urlVersion=0&_userid=10&md5=84eaf5dbbe5df501cb963e9082924368 | journal = Comptes Rendus Palevol | last1 = Teyssèdre | volume = 6 | issue = 503 | pages = 508–510 | date = 2003 | last =
| doi=10.1016/j.crpv.2003.09.023 }}</ref>
''Tawuia'' describes a more sausage- or crescent-shaped fossil; ''Chuaria'' refers to more discoial instances.
The fossils are often preserved as organic compressions. They are considered to represent microbial structures;<ref name=trois /> some authors consider them to be affiliated with [[slime mold]]s<ref name=trois /> [[Stratigraphic]]ally, they range from {{Ma|1630}}<ref>{{Cite journal| first1 = P.| first2 = R. | title = Proterozoic carbonaceous remains from the Chorhat Sandstone: oldest fossils of the Vindhyan Supergroup, Central India | journal = Geobios | volume = 39| issue = 6| last1 = Srivastava | pages = 873–878 | year = 2006 | doi = 10.1016/j.geobios.2006.02.001| last2 = Bali}}</ref> to the late [[Ediacaran]].<ref>{{Cite journal| first1 = D. V.| last1 = Grazhdankin | first2 = K. E.| first3 = A. V. | title = Late Vendian Miaohe-type ecological assemblage of the east European platform | journal = Doklady Earth Sciences | volume = 417 | pages = 1183–1187 | year = 2007 | doi = 10.1134/S1028334X07080107| last2 = Nagovitsin| last3 = Maslov|bibcode = 2007DokES.417.1183G }}</ref>
''Chuaria'' is multicellular.<!-- {{ref doi|10.1130/G38680.1}} -->
